","1324":"1324","1367":"1367","1366":"1366","1320":"1320","1342":"1342","1375":"1375","1328":"1328","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Scotland","Auchterarder, Perth, Scotland":"Auchterarder, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Cargill, Perthshire, Scotland":"Cargill, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Tonbridge, Kent, England":"Tonbridge, Kent, England","Stobhall, Cargill, Perthshire, Scotland":"Cargill, Perthshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Montifex Baron of Cargill was born in 1305, in Cargill, Perthshire, Scotland, his father, Laurence de Montefichet, was 35 and his mother, Countess Rohais Montifex Countess of Gloucester, was 25. He had at least 1 daughter with Mary De Monteith. In 1311, his occupation is listed as governor of dundee. He died in 1366, in Auchterarder, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 61, and was buried in Perthshire, Scotland."},"et":{"1305–1366":"1305–1366","1295–1367":"1295–1367","1330–1375":"1330–1375","1324–1424":"1324–1424","–1368":"–1368","1270–1347":"1270–1347","1280–1342":"1280–1342","13 April 1342":"13. aprill 1342","1330":"1330","from 1311 to 1312":"1311 kuni 1312","from 1319 to 1333":"1319 kuni 1333","1295":"1295","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1305":"1305","1347":"1347","1424":"1424","1368":"1368","1324":"1324","1367":"1367","1366":"1366","1320":"1320","1342":"1342","1375":"1375","1328":"1328","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Scotland","Auchterarder, Perth, Scotland":"Auchterarder, Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Cargill, Perthshire, Scotland":"Cargill, Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Tonbridge, Kent, England":"Tonbridge, Kent, England","Stobhall, Cargill, Perthshire, Scotland":"Cargill, Perthshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1305–1366":"1305–1366","1295–1367":"1295–1367","1330–1375":"1330–1375","1324–1424":"1324–1424","–1368":"–1368","1270–1347":"1270–1347","1280–1342":"1280–1342","13 April 1342":"13. huhtikuuta 1342","1330":"1330","from 1311 to 1312":"vuodesta 1311 vuoteen 1312","from 1319 to 1333":"vuodesta 1319 vuoteen 1333","1295":"1295","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1305":"1305","1347":"1347","1424":"1424","1368":"1368","1324":"1324","1367":"1367","1366":"1366","1320":"1320","1342":"1342","1375":"1375","1328":"1328","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Scotland","Auchterarder, Perth, Scotland":"Auchterarder, Perthshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cargill, Perthshire, Scotland":"Cargill, Perthshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Tonbridge, Kent, England":"Tonbridge, Kent, Eng